   "source": [
    "# Special (Dunder) Methods in Python\n",
    "\n",
    "Special methods \u2014 also called **magic methods** or **dunder methods** (short for *double underscore*) \u2014 let your custom classes hook into Python's built-in syntax and behavior.\n",
    "\n",
    "When you write `len(obj)`, `obj1 + obj2`, or `for x in obj`, Python is secretly calling a special method on `obj` behind the scenes.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook walks through the 12 most common special methods, with runnable examples for each:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Constructor \u2014 `__init__()`\n",
    "2. String representation \u2014 `__str__()`, `__repr__()`\n",
    "3. Length \u2014 `__len__()`\n",
    "4. Equality \u2014 `__eq__()`\n",
    "5. Operator overloading \u2014 `__add__()`, `__sub__()`, `__mul__()`\n",
    "6. Item access \u2014 `__getitem__()`\n",
    "7. Item assignment \u2014 `__setitem__()`\n",
    "8. Membership testing \u2014 `__contains__()`\n",
    "9. Callable objects \u2014 `__call__()`\n",
    "10. Iteration support \u2014 `__iter__()`, `__next__()`\n",
    "11. Boolean evaluation \u2014 `__bool__()`\n",
    "12. Destructor \u2014 `__del__()`\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Constructor \u2014 `__init__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "`__init__()` is called automatically right after an object is created. It's where you set up the object's initial state (its attributes).\n",
    "\n",
    "> Note: `__init__` initializes an *already created* object. The actual creation happens in `__new__()`, which you rarely need to override.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Point:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, x, y):\n",
    "        self.x = x\n",
    "        self.y = y\n",
    "\n",
    "p = Point(3, 4)\n",
    "print(p.x, p.y)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. String Representation \u2014 `__str__()` and `__repr__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "- `__str__()` is used by `print()` and `str()` \u2014 meant to be **readable** for end users.\n",
    "- `__repr__()` is used by the interactive shell, `repr()`, and as a fallback for `print()` if `__str__` isn't defined \u2014 meant to be **unambiguous**, ideally something you could copy-paste to recreate the object.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Point:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, x, y):\n",
    "        self.x = x\n",
    "        self.y = y\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __str__(self):\n",
    "        return f\"({self.x}, {self.y})\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __repr__(self):\n",
    "        return f\"Point(x={self.x}, y={self.y})\"\n",
    "\n",
    "p = Point(3, 4)\n",
    "print(p)        # uses __str__\n",
    "print(str(p))   # uses __str__\n",
    "print(repr(p))  # uses __repr__\n",
    "p               # in a notebook/REPL, this also uses __repr__\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Length \u2014 `__len__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "Implementing `__len__()` lets your object work with the built-in `len()` function.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Playlist:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, songs):\n",
    "        self.songs = songs\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __len__(self):\n",
    "        return len(self.songs)\n",
    "\n",
    "playlist = Playlist([\"Song A\", \"Song B\", \"Song C\"])\n",
    "print(len(playlist))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Equality \u2014 `__eq__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "By default, `==` compares object identity (like `is`). Defining `__eq__()` lets you customize what it means for two objects of your class to be \"equal\" (e.g., comparing their data instead of their memory address).\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Point:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, x, y):\n",
    "        self.x = x\n",
    "        self.y = y\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __eq__(self, other):\n",
    "        if not isinstance(other, Point):\n",
    "            return NotImplemented\n",
    "        return self.x == other.x and self.y == other.y\n",
    "\n",
    "p1 = Point(1, 2)\n",
    "p2 = Point(1, 2)\n",
    "p3 = Point(5, 5)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(p1 == p2)  # True, even though they're different objects\n",
    "print(p1 == p3)  # False\n",
    "print(p1 is p2)  # False (different objects in memory)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Operator Overloading \u2014 `__add__()`, `__sub__()`, `__mul__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "These let you define what `+`, `-`, and `*` mean for your own objects.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Operator | Method      |\n",
    "|----------|-------------|\n",
    "| `+`      | `__add__`   |\n",
    "| `-`      | `__sub__`   |\n",
    "| `*`      | `__mul__`   |\n",
    "| `/`      | `__truediv__` |\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Vector:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, x, y):\n",
    "        self.x = x\n",
    "        self.y = y\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __add__(self, other):\n",
    "        return Vector(self.x + other.x, self.y + other.y)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __sub__(self, other):\n",
    "        return Vector(self.x - other.x, self.y - other.y)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __mul__(self, scalar):\n",
    "        return Vector(self.x * scalar, self.y * scalar)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __repr__(self):\n",
    "        return f\"Vector({self.x}, {self.y})\"\n",
    "\n",
    "v1 = Vector(2, 3)\n",
    "v2 = Vector(1, 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(v1 + v2)   # Vector(3, 4)\n",
    "print(v1 - v2)   # Vector(1, 2)\n",
    "print(v1 * 3)    # Vector(6, 9)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Item Access \u2014 `__getitem__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "This lets your object support indexing with square brackets, like `obj[0]`, and also enables iteration via `for` loops if `__iter__` isn't defined.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Playlist:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, songs):\n",
    "        self.songs = songs\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __getitem__(self, index):\n",
    "        return self.songs[index]\n",
    "\n",
    "playlist = Playlist([\"Song A\", \"Song B\", \"Song C\"])\n",
    "print(playlist[0])\n",
    "print(playlist[-1])\n",
    "\n",
    "for song in playlist:  # works because __getitem__ exists\n",
    "    print(\"Playing:\", song)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Item Assignment \u2014 `__setitem__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "This lets you assign values using square-bracket syntax, like `obj[key] = value`.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Playlist:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, songs):\n",
    "        self.songs = songs\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __getitem__(self, index):\n",
    "        return self.songs[index]\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __setitem__(self, index, value):\n",
    "        self.songs[index] = value\n",
    "\n",
    "playlist = Playlist([\"Song A\", \"Song B\", \"Song C\"])\n",
    "playlist[1] = \"New Song\"\n",
    "print(playlist.songs)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 8. Membership Testing \u2014 `__contains__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "This powers the `in` keyword for your custom objects.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Playlist:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, songs):\n",
    "        self.songs = songs\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __contains__(self, song):\n",
    "        return song in self.songs\n",
    "\n",
    "playlist = Playlist([\"Song A\", \"Song B\", \"Song C\"])\n",
    "print(\"Song A\" in playlist)\n",
    "print(\"Song Z\" in playlist)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 9. Callable Objects \u2014 `__call__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "If a class defines `__call__()`, its instances can be called like functions: `obj(...)`. This is handy for things like counters, decorators, or stateful function-like objects.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Counter:\n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        self.count = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __call__(self):\n",
    "        self.count += 1\n",
    "        return self.count\n",
    "\n",
    "counter = Counter()\n",
    "print(counter())  # 1\n",
    "print(counter())  # 2\n",
    "print(counter())  # 3\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 10. Iteration Support \u2014 `__iter__()` and `__next__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "To make a fully-fledged **iterator**, implement:\n",
    "- `__iter__()` \u2014 returns the iterator object itself (usually `self`)\n",
    "- `__next__()` \u2014 returns the next value, and raises `StopIteration` when done\n",
    "\n",
    "This is what powers `for` loops, list comprehensions, and the `next()` builtin.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Countdown:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, start):\n",
    "        self.current = start\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __iter__(self):\n",
    "        return self\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __next__(self):\n",
    "        if self.current <= 0:\n",
    "            raise StopIteration\n",
    "        value = self.current\n",
    "        self.current -= 1\n",
    "        return value\n",
    "\n",
    "for number in Countdown(5):\n",
    "    print(number)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 11. Boolean Evaluation \u2014 `__bool__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "This controls how your object behaves in a boolean context, e.g., `if obj:` or `bool(obj)`. Without it, Python falls back to `__len__()` (an object is \"truthy\" if its length is nonzero), and if neither is defined, every object is truthy by default.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Playlist:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, songs):\n",
    "        self.songs = songs\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __bool__(self):\n",
    "        return len(self.songs) > 0\n",
    "\n",
    "empty_playlist = Playlist([])\n",
    "full_playlist = Playlist([\"Song A\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(bool(empty_playlist))  # False\n",
    "print(bool(full_playlist))   # True\n",
    "\n",
    "if full_playlist:\n",
    "    print(\"Playlist has songs!\")\n",
    "\n",
    "if not empty_playlist:\n",
    "    print(\"Playlist is empty!\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 12. Destructor \u2014 `__del__()`\n",
    "\n",
    "`__del__()` is called when an object is about to be destroyed (garbage collected). It's used for cleanup, e.g., closing files or network connections.\n",
    "\n",
    "\u26a0\ufe0f **Caution:** The exact timing of `__del__()` is not guaranteed (it depends on Python's garbage collector), so it shouldn't be relied on for critical cleanup. Prefer context managers (`with` statements, `__enter__`/`__exit__`) for deterministic resource cleanup.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Connection:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, name):\n",
    "        self.name = name\n",
    "        print(f\"Connection '{self.name}' opened.\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __del__(self):\n",
    "        print(f\"Connection '{self.name}' closed.\")\n",
    "\n",
    "conn = Connection(\"Database\")\n",
    "del conn  # explicitly triggers __del__ here\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "| # | Category              | Special Method(s)                  |\n",
    "|---|------------------------|-------------------------------------|\n",
    "| 1 | Constructor            | `__init__()`                       |\n",
    "| 2 | String representation   | `__str__()`, `__repr__()`           |\n",
    "| 3 | Length                  | `__len__()`                         |\n",
    "| 4 | Equality                | `__eq__()`                          |\n",
    "| 5 | Operator overloading    | `__add__()`, `__sub__()`, `__mul__()` |\n",
    "| 6 | Item access             | `__getitem__()`                     |\n",
    "| 7 | Item assignment         | `__setitem__()`                     |\n",
    "| 8 | Membership testing      | `__contains__()`                    |\n",
    "| 9 | Callable objects        | `__call__()`                        |\n",
    "| 10| Iteration support       | `__iter__()`, `__next__()`          |\n",
    "| 11| Boolean evaluation      | `__bool__()`                        |\n",
    "| 12| Destructor              | `__del__()`                         |\n",
    
